The blog can be used to communicate project related information, such as release notes or development roadmaps, to the public.

Creating and publishing Blog Entries

Every project member can create and edit Blog Entries. Once created, Entries are not published by default, to allow for preparation in advance. The Product Owner can choose to publish Blog Entries. Only published Entries will be taken into account when project data is exported.

The calendar can be used to schedule project-related events.

Scrum Meetings: Daily Scrums

There are a number of Scrum-related meetings to be scheduled.

Every Day at the same time (and the same place) a Daily Scrum should be held (and supervised by the Scrum Master). In this status meeting everybody answers three questions:

  • What did you do yesterday?
  • What are you going to do today?
  • Are there any impediments?

Scrum Meetings: Reviews and Retrospectives

At the beginning of a Sprint, the Product Owner invites the Team to do a Scrum Planning Meeting, in which the Team selects Stories from the Product Backlog and commits to complete them during the upcoming Sprint.

At the end of Sprints, Sprint Review and Sprint Retrospective Meetings are held. In Sprint Review Meetings the Team presents their work results to the Product Owner, who then decides to accept or reject the work. In Sprint Retrospectives the Team and the Scrum Master reflect on the past Sprint's work and discuss possible improvements that can be made to future Sprints.

The courtroom can be used to keep track of project participant's rule violations.

Agree on punishment, use the revenue

For example, you could agree on Team Members having to pay one Euro when they are late to Daily Scrum Meetings. Every time a Team Member is late, the number of violations is then increased. When you reach a sufficient amount of money, you can throw a party and use it to buy cake and beer.

The File Repository can be used to upload files that can then be conveniently linked within the project.

Linking uploaded Files

An uploaded file is assigned an ID fleN (where N is some number). When you use this ID somewhere within Kunagi (like in entity descriptions or the chat), a link to the corresponding file is automatically created.

Upload from forms

You can use the upload feature not only in the File Repository view, but also, when editing other entities within the project, using the text editor toolbar.

The forum is a place to have discussions with other project participants.

Types of Subjects

There are two kinds of Subjects visible in the Forum view. Firstly, Subjects created in the Forum view and secondly, discussions that are attached to other entities. You can distinguish them by looking at the entity ID. Independent discussions have IDs like sbjN (where N is some number), whereas discussions attached to some entity have the same ID as the corresponding entity (for example sto42 for a discussion for the Story with the ID sto42).

The Scrum Master uses the Impediment view to keep track of Impediments that encumber the project.

The lifecycle of Impediments

When impediments come up (e. g. are given by a Team Member during a Daily Scrum Meeting), the Scrum Master creates an Impediment to document it's existence. He then works to remove Impediments that obstruct the Team's work. As soon as a solution is found, he closes the Impediment by selecting Close from the entity menu and documents the solution, so then Team Members can check back to see if and how an Impediment was solved.

The Issue view is a place to keep track of feedback, bugs and ideas for the project.

Types of Issues

It is divided into four parts, namely Issue Inbox, Bugs, Ideas and Closed Issues. When an Issue is submitted, it is created in the Inbox.

Product Owner processes the Inbox

The Product Owner reviews all Issues in the Inbox and decides how to handle them. He can choose to postpone a decision by selecting Suspend from the entity menu. Otherwise he selects to convert the Issue to a Bug or an Idea.

Team fixes Bugs

Bugs are the Team's domain and are usually flaws of past work results that have been discovered in later Sprints. When a Sprint Planning Meeting is held and the Team decides on how much work they can handle during the next Sprint, they should also take into account the work that has to be invested into bug solving. In case a bug's scope is too big or otherwise unclear, it might be a better idea to create a Story from it.

Product Owner manages Ideas

Ideas on the other hand are to be handled by the Product Owner. When an Issue is converted to an Idea, it is accepted, but a Story for the Product Backlog is yet to be created.

Closed Issues

Closed Issues are all Issues that have been sufficiently addressed. Solutions of issues include an actual resolution of an issue, identifying it as a duplicate of another issue, creating a story from it or refusing to address it.

The Project Journal chronologically records all of the important events in the project.

Events in the Project Journal

When users make important changes to project data, the event is recorded and placed in the Project Journal. The Journal is mainly used to show the latest events in the Dashboard. Older actions can be looked up in the Project Journal view.

Change Log vs. Project Journal

Changes done to Entities are not recorded here. Instead, they can be viewed by selecting Show Change Log from the entity menu.

The Next Sprint view is used to prepare the next Sprint in advance.

Product Owner prepares Next Sprint

The Product Owner can select a start date and Sprint duration and should give the Sprint a name based on the Sprint Goal. After the Sprint Review Meeting of the current Sprint, the Product Owner selects Switch to this Sprint in order to finish and file the current Sprint and replace it's Sprint Backlog with the new one. All unfinished Stories are then moved back to the Product Backlog and all unfinished Tasks are deleted.

The Product Backlog is a prioritized list of desired product features.

Product Owner creates and prioritizes Product Backlog

The Product Owner is responsible for creating the Product Backlog and keeping it up to date. It contains Stories that describe desired product features. Furthermore, the Stories are prioritized: the more important the feature the higher in the Product Backlog it is placed.

Team select Stories during Sprint Planning

During Sprint Planning Meetings, the Team picks Stories from the top (and only the top) of the Product Backlog and commits to implement them during the upcoming Sprint. By placing the features he wants to see implemented next on top of the Product Backlog, the Product Owner can decide the direction of the project.

Estimating the Product Backlog

Before the Team can start working on Stories, Team Members have to estimate them relative to each other (i. e. a Story estimated with 2 points presumably takes twice as much effort as a 1 point Story). In order for this to be possible, the Product Owner needs to provide a sufficient description and explanation of the Story. Once Stories are pulled to a Sprint, they may not be changed any further. Therefore, the Product Owner should always be present for estimation and explain the Stories to the team (and adjust the it's description and scope if necessary).

As a rule of thumb, there should be enough detailed and estimated Stories for the next two to three Sprints. Putting too much detail into low priotized Stories should be avoided, as details are likely to change in the future.

The Team's Velocity

The Velocity history and average Velocity values show how many Story Points the Team was able to complete in past Sprints and on average. By adjusting the anticipated Velocity value, the Product Owner and other project members can project an approximation of what will be completed in the following Sprints. It also helps the Team to decide, how many Stories they can commit to during the Sprint Planning Meeting.

Qualities are requirements that affect multiple Stories.

What are Qualities?

Some requirements put general demands on the implementation of the project. In that case, those specific requirements are likely to appear in multiple Stories. In order to avoid repetition, Qualities can be created and linked to Stories in the Product Backlog.

Non-functional requirements

Popular examples of such requirements are non-functional requirements in software. When listing functional requirements in a table, non-functional requirements are best imagined on another axis, affecting one or more of the functional requirements.

For example, with Stories listed on the left and Qualities on top and X indicating that a Story and Quality are linked:

  User Documentation Thread Safety
Create User Framework   X
Create Administration View X  
Create Login View X

Releases can be used to keep track of product versions and their specifics.

Types of Releases

The Product Owner can create Releases that represent product versions that are released to the public. There are two types of Releases: Releases and Bugfix Releases. The former represent a major product version while the latter are a minor change to the associated Release (that might be necessary if bugs are found that have to be fixed quickly).

Associating Releases with work results

A Release usually spans a number of Sprints and includes all Stories completed during those Sprints. Additionally, known Bugs can be associated with both types of releases as known (but not fixed) and fixed.

Risks are anticipated events that can have an adverse impact on the project.

Risk Management

Project Members should do Risk Management to avoid project failure due to unexpected occurrence of problems. By anticipating and evaluating possible problems, risk management allows for the project to continue smoothly, even when problems occur.

Evaluating Risks

Risks are evaluated by estimating probability and impact. The probability of a Risk is the likeliness of the risk becoming a problem, while the impact is the damage to the project that might be induced by the problem. By developing probability and impact mitigation plans the Team can reduce probability and impact, thus making a favourable project outcome more likely.

Prioritization of Risks

Risks are prioritized automatically based on probability and impact values according to the following table:

  very likely likely possible unlikely very unlikely
extreme Severe Severe High Significant Moderate
substantial Very High High Significant Moderate Moderate
medium High Significant Moderate Moderate Moderate
minor Significant Moderate Moderate Low Very Low
negligible Moderate Moderate Low Very Low Very Low

Monitoring Risks

Risk should be constantly monitored and reviewed at least once a month. The effectiveness of Risk Management depends on the data being up to date and project members adhering to existing mitigation plans.

The Sprint Backlog is used by the Team to organize their current work.

Select Stories, create Tasks

It consists of Stories selected from the Product Backlog during the preceding Sprint Planning Meeting. For every Story, the Team creates Tasks that — once completed — complete the corresponding Story.

Burning the Sprint Backlog

Only completed Stories count towards the Team's success, therefore work should be concentrated rather than spread across Stories. Figuratively speaking, completing half of each Story means a success rate of 0% while completing half of the Stories means a success rate of 50%.

Product Owner accepts or rejects results

Once there are no Tasks left to do in a Story, the Product Owner can review and accept it as solved during the Sprint Review. When the Sprint ends, only Stories that have been accepted by the Product Owner count towards the Team's Velocity. Stories that are not accepted are moved back to the Product Backlog.

The Whiteboard is a visual representation of the current Sprint's progress.

Moving Tasks on the Whiteboard

It displays the current Sprint Backlog, arranging Tasks to indicate the Sprint's progress. Tasks that are yet untouched are on the left, Tasks that are currently being worked on can be found in the middle and finished Tasks on the right. Like moving sticky notes on a real whiteboard, Team members can move Tasks around, setting them as claimed or completed as they do so.

The Sprint approaches completion as Tasks move from left to right.
